      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nHistidine is among the strongest amino acid chelators for Zn²⁺, owing to its imidazole side chain — the same motif that anchors zinc in zinc-finger proteins and many metalloenzymes (e.g., carbonic anhydrase). The rich speciation seen here — spanning protonated, neutral, and hydroxo complexes — reflects the multiple donor atoms (amino-N, imidazole-N, carboxylate-O) and the strong pH dependence of histidine coordination. The **ZnL₂** species (12 entries, the most measured) is the dominant complex near physiological pH, which is directly relevant to modeling zinc transport and bioavailability in biological fluids — precisely the context of the Berthon handbook in which this chapter appears.\n\n*Data source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46).*",
